Chapter 10. <eos/><bos/>As explained there and in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs9:9" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If31d51406b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 9:9</cite.query>, the majority of transferred cases are never remanded. <eos/><bos/>Under the pre-Lexecon practice, many cases were transferred to the transferee court for all purposes. <eos/><bos/>Although than practice was halted by Lexecon,[<footnote.reference refid="If31d51416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">2</footnote.reference>] the transferee court is still able to decide dispositive motions or preside over settlement of the actions, in either case obviating remand.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel Rules provide for remand, however, by two mechanisms. <eos/><bos/>The Panel may initiate remand either by conditional remand order[<footnote.reference refid="If31d51426b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">3</footnote.reference>] or order to show cause why remand should not be ordered.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d51446b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">4</footnote.reference>] In all significant respects, these two methods of implementing remand are procedurally similar to their “transfer” relatives, the conditional transfer order and order to show cause why transfer should not be ordered.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d51456b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">5</footnote.reference>] In each case the rules provide a chance for a party to object to transfer and to have the matter heard on the merits if an objection is timely made. <eos/><bos/>Notice of objection to a conditional remand order must be followed by a motion to vacate the order.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d78516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">6</footnote.reference>] As is true for conditional transfer orders, failure to object to a conditional remand order will be deemed by the Panel as acquiescence in the order.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d78526b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Remand may be initiated by any of three events: the motion of any party, suggestion of the transferee court, or the Panel&apos;s own initiative.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d78536b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">8</footnote.reference>] In the absence of a formal notice of suggestion of remand by the transferee court, however, remand is unlikely.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d78546b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">9</footnote.reference>] The Panel Rules discourage motions for remand by the parties to some degree by requiring that such a motion be accompanied by an affidavit reciting whether the movant has requested that the transferee judge issue a suggestion of remand, the judge&apos;s response, and whether the parties have complied with all pretrial orders.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d9f616b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">10</footnote.reference>] As a practical matter, remand may be more profitably sought by bringing a motion in the transferee court seeking a suggestion of remand from the transferee judge.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="If31d9f626b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><author.footnotes><footnote ID="If31d03216b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>a0</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></author.footnotes><footnote.block><footnote ID="If31d2a306b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546" ID="I59e0a6306b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407(a)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The statute is reproduced in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs3:19" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If31d2a316b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 3:19</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d51416b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-serial-number="1998061318" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="I59e190926b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Lexecon Inc. v. Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &amp; Lerach, 523 U.S. 26, 118 S. Ct. 956, 140 L. Ed. 2d 62 (1998)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d51426b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>J.P.M.L. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59e49dd06b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">R. 10.2</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel Rules are reprinted in their entirety in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:34" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If31d51436b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:34</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d51446b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Panel <cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59e699a06b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 10.1(b)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d51456b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>These methods of implementing transfer are discussed in greater detail in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs4:4" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If31d78506b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 4:4</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d78516b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Panel <cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59ed9e806b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 10.2(b) &amp; (e)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d78526b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Panel <cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.2" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59f00f806b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 10.2(c)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d78536b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Panel <cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.1" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59f232606b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 10.1(b)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d78546b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Panel <cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.3" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59f566b06b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 10.3(a)(d)</cite.query>. <eos/><bos/>The Panel&apos;s reluctance to order remand in the absence of a notice of suggestion of remand from the transferee judge is discussed in <cite.query w-ref-type="NA" w-normalized-cite="MDLITMANs10:6" w-pub-number="185218" ID="If31d9f606b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2">§ 10:6</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d9f616b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Panel <cite.query w-src-number="0304913999" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="USMULTIDISTLITR10.3" w-pub-number="1000604" ID="I59f7b0a06b3e11e9a5a983883834314b">Rule 10.3(a)(i)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="If31d9f626b3e11e99b03e53d6dd36aa2"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Panel&apos;s decisions relating to the merits of remand are discussed in Chapter 10.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>MDLITMAN § 4:32<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
